<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06333185 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06333185 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SO-CALIF; SAN-BERNARDINO; COUNTY; TREE; FIRE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Firefighters surrounded a brush fire that burned 127 acres in the SanBernardino National Forest on Wednesday and briefly forced the closing of astate highway.;   The fire was expected to be controlled by 6 p.m. today, saidU.S. Forest Service spokeswoman Judy Behrens. She said some of the 150firefighters who fought the blaze would remain to ensure control.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  127 ACRES SCORCHED IN SAN BERNARDINO  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;About 30 people will probably be sitting on a rock eating Thanksgivingdinner,&quot; Behrens said.;   Four firefighters suffered minor injuries battlingthe blaze on rocky hillsides about five miles north of San Bernardino, about60 miles east of downtown Los Angeles.;   No structures were threatened by thebrush fire, which had forced the closing of Highway 330 for several hoursWednesday. The road was reopened at 12:30 p.m.;   The highway, a key route toBig Bear Lake, a popular weekend getaway, was closed just outside thecommunity of Highland three miles north of San Bernardino.;   The cause of thefire was under investigation.;   Meanwhile, investigators looking into aSylmar fire that burned 750 acres of brush were told by witnesses that sparksfell from hillside power lines before the blaze erupted Monday.;   But utilitycompanies disputed the accounts Tuesday, saying that their equipment did notmalfunction until after the fire started. Several ranch buildings were damagedby flames.;   Los Angeles fire officials said the cause of the blaze remainsunder investigation.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  San Bernardino  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911128  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  6G 